{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507953"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:59:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:59:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2697"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2697"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.04,0.43,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"21400"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2697"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"10448"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3320"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3335"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"21400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/21400"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with new onset weakness. She describes right sided leg and arm weakness for the last 3 hours. She initially tried to walk and has fallen several times before calling an ambulance. She has some trouble speaking, especially with words containing multiple syllables. She has a past medical history of hypertension, and hypercholesterolaemia. She has a 40 pack year smoking history. On examination, she is right handed and her face is symmetrical. She is slurring words and struggling to pronounce words during much of the history. In her upper limb, her right arm is 4/5 power throughout and 5/5 on the left. She has a positive grasp reflex on the right more than the left.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has 2/5 power in her right leg and 5/5 on left. Her coordination is grossly impaired on the right compared to the left. She has reduced fine touch on the right compared to the left side.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cerebral blood vessels is most likely to be affected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left middle cerebral artery","Right middle cerebral artery","Left anterior cerebral artery","Right anterior cerebral artery","Left posterior cerebral artery"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAll of the cerebral blood vessels have classical clinical syndromes based on the cortical lobes and subcortical areas they supply. Important to note is the handedness of the patient to help determine the dominant lobe, which in right handed people is usually the left and in left handed individuals it is 50-50 each way.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe main cortical signs that occur in anterior cerebral artery (ACA), middle cerebral artery (MCA), and posterior cerebral artery (PCA) strokes include weakness, sensory disturbance, visual changes, aphasia (dominant lobe), and neglect (non-dominant).\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe above patient describes right sided weakness worse in the lower limb, right sided sensory loss, dysarthria, limb ataxia, gait apraxia and frontal signs. This is all in keeping with \u003Cstrong\u003EACA territory on the left side \u003C/strong\u003Ebeing affected.\u0026nbsp;It is important to note sensory loss and weakness are not localising signs, as they can be affected in several different areas. The ACA supplies the territory along the longitudinal fissure dividing the two hemispheres. It supplies the medial frontal lobe, and parietal lobe. ACA infarcts are rare due to collateral blood vessel supply by the anterior communicating artery and their anatomical origin, however any infarct distal to A1 (i.e. beyond ACOM) will give the above deficits.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In the presence of cortical weakness and sensory loss affecting legs more than arms, consider a cerebrovascular event involving the anterior cerebral artery (ACA)."],"references":["Arboix A, Garcia-Eroles L, Sellares N, Raga A, Oliveres M, Massons J. Infarction in the territory of the anterior cerebral artery: clinical study of 51 patients. BMC Neurology. 2009; 30."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"10448"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2697"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"10448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/10448"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-03-09T20:48:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-03-09T20:48:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2697"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"21400"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72",